Gutmann and Hyvarinen, 2010, **Noise-contrastive estimation: A new
estimation principle for unnormalized statistical models**, *AISTATS*.
[pdf](http://proceedings.mlr.press/v9/gutmann10a/gutmann10a.pdf)

<div id="density-estimation-problem" class="section level1">

Density Estimation Problem
==========================

-   Given a sample of a random vector [\\(\\mathbf{x}
    \\in \\mathbb{R}\^n\\)]{.math .inline} from an unknown pdf
    [\\(p\_d(\\cdot)\\)]{.math .inline}
-   Our model: a parameterized family of functions
    [\\(\\lbrace p\_m(\\cdot;\\alpha) \\rbrace\_{\\alpha}\\)]{.math
    .inline}
-   How to estimate [\\(\\alpha\\)]{.math .inline} from the observed
    sample by maximizing some objective function?
-   Any solution to this estimation problem must yield a normalized
    density\
    \
    [\\\[ \\begin{aligned} & p\_m(\\cdot;\\alpha) =
    \\frac{p\_m\^0(\\cdot;\\alpha)}{Z(\\alpha)} \\\\\[11pt\]
    & Z(\\alpha) = \\int p\_m\^0(\\mathbf{u};\\alpha) d\\mathbf{u}
    \\end{aligned} \\\]]{.math .display}\
    \
-   However, the calculation of [\\(Z(\\alpha)\\)]{.math .inline} is
    very problematic

------------------------------------------------------------------------

</div>

<div id="noise-constrative-estimator" class="section level1">

Noise-Constrative Estimator
===========================

-   Learning by comparison: by discriminating between data and noise,
    learn properties of the data in the from of a statistical model
-   Definition
    -   Including the [\\(Z(\\alpha)\\)]{.math .inline} as another
        parameter [\\(c\\)]{.math .inline}\
        \
        [\\\[ \\begin{aligned} & \\log p\_m(\\cdot;\\theta) =
        \\log p\_m\^0(\\cdot;\\alpha) + c \\\\\[11pt\] & \\theta =
        \\lbrace \\alpha, c \\rbrace \\end{aligned} \\\]]{.math
        .display}\
        \
    -   [\\(c\\)]{.math .inline}: an estimate of the negative logarithm
        of [\\(Z(\\alpha)\\)]{.math .inline}
    -   [\\(p\_m(\\cdot;\\theta)\\)]{.math .inline} will only integrate
        to one for some specific choice of [\\(c\\)]{.math .inline}
-   Observations
    -   Observed data: [\\(X = \\lbrace \\mathbf{x}\_1, \\cdots,
        \\mathbf{x}\_T \\rbrace \\sim p\_m(\\cdot;\\theta)\\)]{.math
        .inline}
    -   Noise (artificial generated): [\\(Y = \\lbrace \\mathbf{y}\_1,
        \\cdots, \\mathbf{y}\_T \\rbrace \\sim p\_n(\\cdot)\\)]{.math
        .inline}
    -   Union of [\\(X\\)]{.math .inline} and [\\(Y\\)]{.math .inline}:
        [\\(U = \\lbrace \\mathbf{u} \_1, \\cdots, \\mathbf{u}
        \_{2T} \\rbrace\\)]{.math .inline}
    -   [\\(C\_t\\)]{.math .inline}: Binary class label of
        [\\(\\mathbf{u}\_t\\)]{.math .inline}\
        \
        [\\\[ \\begin{aligned} C\_t = \\begin{cases} 1 & \\mathbf{u}\_t
        \\in X \\\\\[11pt\] 0 & \\mathbf{u}\_t \\in Y \\end{cases}
        \\end{aligned} \\\]]{.math .display}\
        \
-   Objective function [\\(J\_T(\\theta)\\)]{.math .inline}\
    \
    [\\\[ \\begin{aligned} & G(\\mathbf{u} ; \\theta) = \\log
    p\_m(\\mathbf{u} ; \\theta) - \\log p\_n(\\mathbf{u}) \\\\\[11pt\] &
    h(\\mathbf{u} ; \\theta) = \\frac{1}{1 + \\exp(-G(\\mathbf{u} ;
    \\theta))} \\\\\[11pt\] & J\_T(\\theta) = \\frac{1}{2T} \\sum\_t
    \\left( \\log h(\\mathbf{x}\_t ; \\theta) + \\log (1 -
    h(\\mathbf{y}\_t ; \\theta)) \\right) \\\\\[11pt\] &
    \\hat{\\theta}\_T = \\text{argmax}\_{\\theta} J\_T(\\theta)
    \\end{aligned} \\\]]{.math .display}\
    \
    -   Class-conditional probability\
        \
        [\\\[ \\begin{aligned} & P( \\mathbf{u} | C=1 ; \\theta)
        = p\_m(\\mathbf{u};\\theta) \\\\\[11pt\] & P(\\mathbf{u} | C
        = 0) = p\_n(\\mathbf{u}) \\end{aligned} \\\]]{.math .display}\
        \
    -   Posterior probability\
        \
        [\\\[ \\begin{aligned} P(C=1 | \\mathbf{u} ; \\theta) & =
        \\frac{P( \\mathbf{u} | C=1 ; \\theta) P(C=1)}{P(\\mathbf{u} ;
        \\theta)} \\\\\[11pt\] & = \\frac{p\_m(\\mathbf{u} ;
        \\theta)}{p\_m(\\mathbf{u} ; \\theta) + p\_n(\\mathbf{u})}
        \\\\\[11pt\] & = h(\\mathbf{u} ; \\theta) \\\\\[11pt\] P(C=0 |
        \\mathbf{u} ; \\theta) & = 1 - h(\\mathbf{u} ; \\theta)
        \\end{aligned} \\\]]{.math .display}\
        \
    -   Log-likelihood for Bernoulli-distributed [\\(C\_t\\)]{.math
        .inline}\
        \
        [\\\[ \\begin{aligned} \\mathcal{l}(\\theta) & = \\sum\_t (C\_t
        \\log P(C\_t = 1|\\mathbf{u}\_t ; \\theta) + (1 - C\_t) \\log
        P(C\_t = 0|\\mathbf{u}\_t ; \\theta)) \\\\\[11pt\] & = \\sum\_t
        \\left( \\log h(\\mathbf{x}\_t ; \\theta) + \\log (1 -
        h(\\mathbf{y}\_t ; \\theta)) \\right) \\end{aligned} \\\]]{.math
        .display}\
        \

------------------------------------------------------------------------

</div>

Example with R
==============

-   Observations
    -   Observed data: [\\(\\mathbf{x} = (x\_1, x\_2) \\sim \\mathcal{N}
        \_2 (\\mathbf{0}, \\mathbb{I} \_2)\\)]{.math .inline}\
        \
        [\\\[ \\begin{aligned} & p\_d(\\mathbf{x}) = \\frac{1}{2 \\pi}
        \\exp{(\\mathbf{x} \^T \\mathbf{x})} \\\\\[11pt\] &
        \\log p\_d(\\mathbf{x}) = - \\log 2 \\pi - \\frac{1}{2} \\lVert
        \\mathbf{x} \\rVert \_2\^2 = - \\log 2 \\pi - \\frac{1}{2}
        x\_1\^2 - \\frac{1}{2} x\_2\^2 \\end{aligned} \\\]]{.math
        .display}\
        \
    -   Noise: [\\(\\mathbf{y} \\sim \\text{Unif} (\[-3, 3\] \\times
        \[-3, 3\])\\)]{.math .inline}\
        \
        [\\\[ \\begin{aligned} & p\_n(\\mathbf{y}) = \\frac{1}{36}
        \\\\\[11pt\] & \\log p\_n(\\mathbf{y}) = \\log \\frac{1}{36}
        \\end{aligned} \\\]]{.math .display}\
        \

``` {.r}
##### Data generation
# Observed data

d <- 2 # dimension

# Noisy data
s <- 36 # area
y <- cbind(runif(n = n, min = -3, max = 3),
           runif(n = n, min = -3, max = 3))
plot(x, col = "red", xlim = c(-3, 3), ylim = c(-3, 3))
points(x = y[,1], y = y[,2])
```

``` {.r}
# Noise model
fn.log.p.n <- function(y, s) {
  p.n <- 1 / s
  log.p.n <- rep(log(p.n), nrow(y))
  return(log.p.n)
}
```

    [\\\[ \\begin{aligned} & \\log p\_m\^0 (\\mathbf{x} ; \\mathbf{w}) =

``` {.r}
# Our model
# log.p.m.zero <- w1x1 + w2x2 + w3x1^2 + w4x1x2 + x5x2^2
# log.p.m <- log.p.m.zero + c
fn.log.p.m <- function(x, theta) {
  # theta: vectorized parameters for optim
  # ex) theta = c(w.init, c.init)
  len.theta <- length(theta)
  w <- theta[1:(len.theta - 1)] # parameters for unnormalized pdf
  c <- theta[len.theta] # normalization constant
  #
  x.poly <- cbind(x, x[,1] * x[,1], x[,1] * x[,2], x[,2] * x[,2])
  log.p.m.zero <- as.numeric(rbind(x.poly) %*% cbind(w))
  log.p.m <- log.p.m.zero + c
  return(log.p.m)
}
```

``` {.r}
fn.log.p.m(x = x[1:10,], theta = c(w.init, c.init))
```

-   Optimization using BFGS method

``` {.r}
# Loss function
fn.loss <- function(x, theta, y, s) {
  u <- rbind(x, y)
  ix.x <- 1:nrow(x)
  ix.y <- (nrow(x) + 1) : (2 * nrow(x))
  log.p.m <- fn.log.p.m(x = u, theta = theta)
  log.p.n <- fn.log.p.n(y = u, s = s)
  g <- log.p.m - log.p.n
  h.u <- 1 / (1 + exp(-g))
  h.x <- h.u[ix.x]
  h.y <- h.u[ix.y]
  loss <- - mean(log(h.x) + log(1 - h.y))
  return(loss)
}
fn.loss(x = x, theta = c(w.init, c.init), y = y, s = s)
```

    ## [1] 2.205783

``` {.r}
# Optimization
itr <- 500
res.opt <- optim(par = c(w.init, c.init), method = "BFGS",
                 control = list(maxit = itr),
                 fn = fn.loss, x = x, y = y, s = s)
res.opt
```

``` {.r}
# Plot decision boundary using initial parameters
fn.prob.post <- function(x, theta.m, theta.n) {
  log.p.m <- fn.log.p.m(x = x, theta = theta.m)
  log.p.n <- fn.log.p.n(y = x, s = theta.n)
  g <- log.p.m - log.p.n
  pr <- 1 / (1 + exp(-g))
  return(pr)
}
y.hat <- fn.prob.post(x = x.test, theta.m = c(w.init, c.init), theta.n = s)
col <- c()
col[y.hat >= 0.5] <- "lightpink"
col[y.hat < 0.5] <- "grey"
plot(x, col = "red", xlim = c(-3, 3), ylim = c(-3, 3))
points(x = y[,1], y = y[,2])
```

<div id="properties-of-the-estimator" class="section level1">

Properties of the Estimator
===========================

-   The behavior of the estimator [\\(\\hat{\\theta}\_T\\)]{.math
    .inline} when the sample size [\\(T\\)]{.math .inline} becomes
    arbitrarily large
-   [\\(J\_T(\\theta)\\)]{.math .inline} converges in probability to
    [\\(J\\)]{.math .inline}\
    \
    [\\\[ \\begin{aligned} J(\\theta) = \\frac{1}{2} \\mathbb{E}
    \\left\[ \\log h(\\mathbf{x} ; \\theta) + \\log (1 - h(\\mathbf{y}
    ; \\theta)) \\right\] \\end{aligned} \\\]]{.math .display}\
    \
-   Let [\\(\\tilde{J}\\)]{.math .inline} denote the objective
    [\\(J\\)]{.math .inline} seen as a function of [\\(f(\\cdot) = \\log
    p\_m(\\cdot ; \\theta)\\)]{.math .inline}, where
    [\\(r(\\cdot)\\)]{.math .inline} is logistic function\
    \
    [\\\[ \\begin{aligned} \\tilde{J}(\\theta) = \\frac{1}{2}
    \\mathbb{E} \\left\[ \\log r(f(\\mathbf{x}) -
    \\log p\_n(\\mathbf{x})) + \\log (1 - r(f(\\mathbf{x}) -
    \\log p\_n(\\mathbf{x}))) \\right\] \\end{aligned} \\\]]{.math
    .display}\
    \
-   **Theorem 1** (Nonparametric estimation) [\\(\\tilde{J}\\)]{.math
    .inline} attains a maximum at [\\(f(\\cdot) =
    \\log p\_d(\\cdot)\\)]{.math .inline}. There are no other extrema if
    the noise density [\\(p\_n(\\cdot)\\)]{.math .inline} is chosen such
    it is nonzero whenever [\\(p\_d(\\cdot)\\)]{.math .inline} is
    nonzero
    -   The data pdf [\\(p\_d(\\cdot)\\)]{.math .inline} can be found by
        maximization of [\\(\\tilde{J}\\)]{.math .inline}, i.e.by
        learning a classifier under the ideal situation of infinite
        amount of data
-   **Theorem 2** (Consistency) If conditions (a) to (c) are fulfilled
    then [\\(\\hat{\\theta}\_T\\)]{.math .inline} converges in
    probability to [\\(\\theta\^{\\star}\\)]{.math .inline}\
    [\\\[ \\begin{aligned} \\\\ & \\text{(a) } p\_n(\\cdot) \\text{ is
    nonzero whenever } p\_d(\\cdot) \\text{ is nonzero} \\\\\[11pt\]
    & \\text{(b) } \\sup\_{\\theta} | J\_T(\\theta) - J(\\theta) |
    \\xrightarrow{P} 0 \\\\\[11pt\] & \\text{(c) } I =
    \\int \\mathbf{g}(\\mathbf{x})
    \\mathbf{g}(\\mathbf{x})\^T P(\\mathbf{x}) p\_d(\\mathbf{x})
    d\\mathbf{x} \\text{ has full rank}, \\\\\[11pt\] & \\quad \\quad
    \\text{where } P(\\mathbf{x})
    = \\frac{p\_n(\\mathbf{x})}{p\_d(\\mathbf{x}) + p\_n(\\mathbf{x})}
    \\text{ and } \\mathbf{g}(\\mathbf{x}) = \\nabla \_{\\theta} \\log
    p\_m(\\mathbf{x} ; \\theta) |\_{\\theta\^{\\star}} \\end{aligned}
    \\\]]{.math .display}\
    \
    -   [\\(\\hat{\\theta}\_T\\)]{.math .inline} that the value of
        [\\(\\theta\\)]{.math .inline} which globally maximizes
        [\\(J\_T\\)]{.math .inline} converges to
        [\\(\\theta\^{\\star}\\)]{.math .inline} and leads to the
        correct estimate of [\\(p\_d(\\cdot)\\)]{.math .inline} as the
        sample size [\\(T\\)]{.math .inline} increases
-   **Theorem 3** (Asymptotic normality) [\\(\\sqrt{T}(\\hat{\\theta} -
    \\theta\^{\\star})\\)]{.math .inline} is asymptotically normal with
    mean zero and covariance matrix [\\(\\Sigma\\)]{.math .inline}\
    \
    [\\\[ \\begin{aligned} \\Sigma = I\^{-1} - 2I\^{-1} \\left\[
    \\int \\mathbf{g}(\\mathbf{x}) P(\\mathbf{x}) p\_d(\\mathbf{x})
    d\\mathbf{x} \\right\] \\left\[ \\int
    \\mathbf{g}(\\mathbf{x})\^T P(\\mathbf{x}) p\_d(\\mathbf{x})
    d\\mathbf{x} \\right\] I\^{-1} \\end{aligned} \\\]]{.math .display}\
    \
    -   This describes the distribution of the estimation error
        [\\((\\hat{\\theta} - \\theta\^{\\star})\\)]{.math .inline} for
        large sample sizes
-   **Corollary 1** For large sample size [\\(T\\)]{.math .inline}, the
    mean squared error [\\(\\mathbb{E} \\lVert \\hat{\\theta} -
    \\theta\^{\\star} \\rVert \^2\\)]{.math .inline} behaves like
    [\\(\\text{tr}(\\Sigma) / T\\)]{.math .inline}

------------------------------------------------------------------------

<div id="choice-of-the-noise-distribution" class="section level1">

Choice of the Noise Distribution
================================

-   In practice, wed like to have a noise distribution which fulfills
    the following:
    1.  It is easy to sample from, since the method relies on a set of
        samples [\\(Y\\)]{.math .inline} from the noise distribution
    2.  It allows for an analytical expression for the log-pdf, so that
        we can evaluate the objective function without any problems
    3.  It leads to a small jmean squared error [\\(\\mathbb{E} \\lVert
        \\hat{\\theta} - \\theta\^{\\star} \\rVert \^2\\)]{.math
        .inline}
-   Noise distribution sould be close to the data distribution, because
    otherwise, the classification problem might be too easy and would
    not require the system to learn much about the structure of the data

------------------------------------------------------------------------

<div id="simulations-with-artificial-data" class="section level1">

Simulations with Artificial Data
================================

-   Data [\\(\\mathbf{x} \\in \\mathbb{R}\^4\\)]{.math .inline} is
    generated via the ICA model\
    \
    [\\\[ \\begin{aligned} & \\mathbf{s} \\sim Laplace (0,1)
    \\\\\[11pt\] & A = (\\mathbf{a}\_1, \\cdots, \\mathbf{a}\_4) \\qquad
    (4 \\times 4) \\text{ mixing matrix} \\\\\[11pt\] &
    \\log p\_d(\\mathbf{x}) = - \\sum\_{i=1}\^4 \\sqrt{2}
    |\\mathbf{b}\_i\^{\\star} \\mathbf{x}| + (\\log
    |\\text{det}(B\^{\\star})| - \\log 4) \\\\\[11pt\] & B\^{\\star} =
    A\^{-1} \\\\\[11pt\] & \\mathbf{b}\_i\^{\\star}: i \\text{-th row of
    } B\^{\\star} \\\\\[11pt\] & c\^{\\star} = \\log
    |\\text{det}(B\^{\\star})| - \\log 4 \\end{aligned} \\\]]{.math
    .display}\
    \
-   Model\
    \
    [\\\[ \\begin{aligned} & \\log p\_m(\\mathbf{x} ; \\theta) = \\log
    p\_m\^0(\\mathbf{x} ; \\alpha) + c \\\\\[11pt\] & \\log p\_m\^0
    (\\mathbf{x} ; \\alpha) = - \\sum\_{i=1}\^4 \\sqrt{2}
    |\\mathbf{b}\_i\^{\\star} \\mathbf{x}| \\\\\[11pt\] & \\text{Total
    set of parameters } \\theta = \\lbrace \\alpha \\in
    \\mathbb{R}\^{16}, c \\rbrace \\end{aligned} \\\]]{.math .display}\
    \
-   Estimation method
    -   Noise: Gaussian with the same mean and covariance matrix as
        [\\(\\mathbf{x}\\)]{.math .inline}
    -   Using conjugate gradient algorithm
